# TinkerPad — Two-Year Plan

*Written 2026-07-03, restructured 2026-07-05. This is a narrative snapshot of the
roadmap, not the roadmap itself. The **lit backlog is the single source of truth**
for what work exists, its order, and its detail — run `lit backlog` for the live
queue. This document captures what the ticket queue cannot: the whole-picture
rationale, the gate story, and where each epic traces back to
[`PROJECT.md`](./PROJECT.md). If this doc and lit disagree, lit wins; if this doc
and PROJECT.md disagree on intent, PROJECT.md wins.*

---

## Where we are (verified, not assumed)

The core loop — **describe → generate → store → discover → use → remix** — is
**built and verified end-to-end**. Driven live through a real browser against
`just dev`:

- Landing page (redesigned: design-token system, light/dark mode, nav, hero,
  create widget) renders and functions.
- Loopback dev login completes the real session dance (CSRF state round-trip,
  cookie minting) with no GitHub app required.
- A prompt typed into the box produced a working playground via the local tmux
  driver running Claude Code: a bouncing-ball physics simulator with presets,
  sliders, and live canvas — stored, served from the sandboxed content origin,
  and playable.
- Player chrome works: attribution, recipe display, Refine input, Remix button,
  Copy Prompt.

One real bug was found and fixed during verification: the OAuth callback URL
defaulted to `127.0.0.1` while browsers visit `localhost`; cookies are
hostname-scoped, so the CSRF state cookie never arrived and every dev login
failed. Fixed in the shared server config as its own commit.

**Implication for the plan:** the foundation is real. Everything below is
deepening, hardening, and reach — not rescue.

---

## The organizing principle: content first, gates not calendars

The 2026-07-05 restructure replaced calendar horizons with **loop-maturity
gates** — each gate has a checkable exit, and progress is measured by which gate
is open, not by which month it is. Two convictions drive the shape:

1. **The playgrounds are the focal point.** Every surface (grid, search, tags,
   thumbnails, trending) is worthless against an empty catalog, and subtly wrong
   if designed against a hypothetical one. Content precedes chrome.
2. **Public exposure is a structural gate, not a date.** The moment TinkerPad
   faces the open internet is encoded as a lit ticket
   (`tinkerpadai-launch-nkn`, "Public launch readiness gate") whose dependency
   edges *are* the launch criteria. Closing it is launching. No prose checklist
   to forget.

The backlog holds **24 epics plus two standalone gate tickets**. Every one
traces to PROJECT.md's two pillars (*frictionless creation*, *the commons*), its
safety mandate, or one of its explicitly open decisions.

Detail follows grooming discipline: near-term tickets are implementer-ready;
far tickets are deliberately sparse because detail written years early is
fiction that rots. Detail gets added as work rises — never before.

---

## Gate 1 — the loop is verified ✅ (done)

Exit criteria: a prompt in a browser becomes a stored, playable, refinable,
remixable playground, end to end. **Passed 2026-07-01.**

## Gate 2 — a commons worth browsing

Exit criteria: 100+ curated playgrounds live, spanning all six PROJECT.md types;
the front-door surfaces are designed against that real content.

| Epic | What it delivers |
|---|---|
| `seeding` (top of queue) | First wave of 25 playgrounds across all six types — as much a generation stress test as a content drop; every loop failure becomes a filed ticket. Then scale to 100. Seeding IS loop-hardening. |
| `quality-ppu.1`: self-containment validation | The contract enforced at the storage boundary before the catalog scales to 100 — an explicit lit edge blocks the scale-up on it, so validation lands after the 25-wave stress test but before mass generation |
| `design-pw7` | Design system applied everywhere it isn't: commons page, player chrome, homepage grid, error pages, favicon — now built against real content |
| `discovery-rye` (near half) | Tags, search, thumbnails, types filter, pagination — meaningful only with a seeded catalog |
| `profile-ek4` | My-playgrounds, OpenGraph cards, public creator pages |

## Gate 3 — safe to expose publicly

Exit criteria: the launch-gate ticket's dependency edges, verbatim. These are
the cheap, launch-gating *slices* pulled forward; the expensive builds behind
them stay in Gate 4.

| Gate item | Why it gates launch |
|---|---|
| Generation economics **decision** (`economics-k91`) | Who pays — platform, BYOK, credits — shapes the provider driver, rate limits, and accounts. The decision lands in PROJECT.md; the build epic stays later. |
| `sandbox`: adversarial audit + rate limits | PROJECT.md: safety designed in from day one. Audit blocks public exposure as a structural edge. |
| `moderation`: report + unlist | A public UGC platform with no takedown path is an incident with a countdown. Review-queue polish can follow launch; the minimal pair cannot. |
| `legal`: terms, privacy, DMCA | Safe harbor requires the agent and procedure before the complaint arrives |
| `cloudflare-8le`: the public deploy | The launch edge itself. `homelab-28m` rehearses the deploy earlier by rank as a staging step — it is not a launch edge in lit. |
| **`launch-nkn`** | The gate ticket. Blocked by all of the above plus the seeded commons. Closing it is launching. |

## Gate 4 — the loop deepens

Exit criteria: creation, iteration, and provenance are all first-class in public.

| Epic | Why it exists |
|---|---|
| `history-3o7` (remainder) | Durable per-turn provider context (needs the deploy targets' durable storage) |
| `providers` | API-based Claude driver behind the same seam — cloud generation isn't real without it — plus live progress streaming |
| `ops` | Tested commons backup/restore, logs, metrics. The commons is the product; losing it is existential. |
| `editing` | PROJECT.md open decision (regenerate vs direct edit vs both); view-source and download land first — portability is the point |
| `social` | Stars, view counts, remix lineage tree; these signals feed trending |
| `versions` | The user surface over history's provenance data |

## Gate 5 — reach and bets

Deliberately sparse; these get detail when they get close.

| Epic | The bet |
|---|---|
| `collections` | Featured, playground-of-the-day, weekly tinker challenge |
| `embed` | Same sandboxed iframe, embedded elsewhere; oEmbed |
| `onboarding` | Prompt tips and gallery *beside* the box, never in front of it |
| `a11y` | WCAG AA + keyboard on all chrome we own |
| `api` | Public read API + MCP server — agents browsing and creating playgrounds |
| `accounts` | More IdPs, settings, deletion policy (the commons outlives its authors) |
| `economics` (build) | Implement whatever Gate 3's decision chose |
| `education` | Classrooms — validate demand before building |

---

## Structural facts worth knowing

- **Launch is a ticket, not a date.** `tinkerpadai-launch-nkn` is blocked by the
  sandbox audit, both moderation slices, both legal slices, the economics
  decision, the seeded commons, and the Cloudflare deploy. Self-containment
  validation gates launch transitively: it blocks the scale-to-100, which blocks
  launch. `lit doctor` verifies the graph stays coherent.
- **Decisions precede builds as edges**: the economics decision ticket blocks
  the economics build epic. The editing epic carries the same decision-gated
  note internally.
- **Cross-epic dependencies are explicit in lit**, not folklore: history blocks
  the versions surface; stars/views block trending. Within an epic, rank
  carries the order.
- **Capacity assumption:** one builder plus agents, working the queue top-down.
  The two-year span is a consequence of the gates, not a promise.

## What this plan refuses to do

Consistent with PROJECT.md's "what TinkerPad is NOT": no blank-canvas editor, no
general app hosting, no private-by-default, no playground that needs a live
backend. Any future epic that violates self-containment or splits sandbox
enforcement across features is wrong by construction, regardless of how
attractive the feature is.
